  "prompt": "How does backpropagation happen in a feed-forward neural network when there is nothing connecting the output to input?",
  "response": "In a feed-forward neural network, backpropagation is the process of calculating the gradient of the loss function with respect to each weight in the network, which is then used to update the weights during training. Here's how it works:\n\n1. Forward Pass:\n- Input is passed through the network\n- Activations are computed layer by layer\n- Final output is compared to the target/true value\n\n2. Loss Calculation:\n- A loss function (e.g., Mean Squared Error) measures the difference between predicted and actual output\n\n3. Backpropagation Process:\n- The gradient of the loss is computed starting from the output layer\n- Using the chain rule, gradients are propagated backwards through the network\n- Each layer's weights are updated based on their contribution to the error\n\nKey points:\n- Backpropagation doesn't require direct connection from output to input\n- Gradients are computed layer by layer using the chain rule\n- Weights are updated to minimize the loss function\n\nThe process relies on:\n- Differentiable activation functions\n- Gradient computation\n- Iterative weight updates\n\nMathematically, this involves computing \u2202L/\u2202w for each weight w, where L is the loss.",
